Ms Kimingi advised that any student suspected of having Covid-19 should be taken to the nearest health facility where he or she will be reviewed and referred accordingly should they meet the case definition for the disease.
On Wednesday, the county’s Department of Education held a sensitisation meeting for all principals of polytechnics, the early childhood development education (ECDE) sub-county education officers as well as sub-county and ward administrators from the county.
Extra classrooms
The officers were taken through the various guidelines and school re-opening directives which they were asked to implement.
Kirinyaga Education Executive Joseph Kinyua said that all the county’s 198 ECDE centres have already re-opened while the 15 polytechnics in the county will be re-opened next week. He noted that the polytechnic principals are members of the zonal Covid-19 committees.
Mr Kinyua also noted that the extra classrooms constructed last year in some ECDE centres and polytechnics will go a long way in enhancing the capacity of the institutions.
He said that during the last financial year, the county government built five ECDE classrooms and renovated 26 others while this year, several new classrooms will be built under a ward-based development programme.



